def: In the sense or manner of a participle.

To beat rapidly and more strongly than usual; to throb; tobound with emotion or exertion; to pulsate violently; to flutter; --said specifically of the heart when its action is abnormal, as fromexcitement.
Flat at the anterior and concave at the posterior end; -- saidof the centra of the vertebræ of some extinct dinouaurs.
To convert again into a forest; to plant again with trees.
Of or pertaining to Samaria, in Palestine.-- n.
Sportive. [Obs.] -- Lu"di*bund*ness, n. [Obs.] Dr. H. More.
A gradual progression from one type to another, generallyascending. Huxley.
Command; precept; injunction. [Archaic] See Behest. "At thyhest." Shak.Let him that yields obey the victor's hest. Fairfax.Yet I thy hest will all perform, at full. Tennyson.
